    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1767142190" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1767142190" />
    <a title="Beth" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/4063913-beth"><img alt="Beth" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1351396026p2/4063913.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1767142190?book_show_action=true">Sep 24, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Beth" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Beth" href="/user/show/4063913-beth">Beth</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4063913-beth?shelf=mg-newbery">mg-newbery</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/4063913-beth?shelf=reviewed">reviewed</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1767142190" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15889775590715740814">It&apos;s Newbery reading time, so I picked this up - and color me impressed. By the book, that is. Which is to say: I closed this and did not think of a medal (though I won&apos;t be upset if this book wins one). <br/><br/>This reads like a middle grade staple. It skews younger in length, depth of story, and complexity. That&apos;s not a dig. This isn&apos;t very long, and the story takes place over a short period of time, meaning there&apos;s not a lot of ground covered. Nor are there complex structural or thematic approaches. </span>
  <span id="freeText15889775590715740814" style="display:none">It's Newbery reading time, so I picked this up - and color me impressed. By the book, that is. Which is to say: I closed this and did not think of a medal (though I won't be upset if this book wins one). <br /><br />This reads like a middle grade staple. It skews younger in length, depth of story, and complexity. That's not a dig. This isn't very long, and the story takes place over a short period of time, meaning there's not a lot of ground covered. Nor are there complex structural or thematic approaches. This is a straightforward story, incredibly well-told. It feels timeless, like it's been on a library shelf for thirty years, or it will be for the next thirty. It breaks no new ground. Its great strength is in its assurance and the directness of its storytelling.<br /><br />There are two fantastic moments: in the restaurant, when two people drop their utensils, and right at the end, when it turns out the result isn't the point at all. <br /><br />This is good stuff.</span>
  <a data-text-id="15889775590715740814" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


